{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"367"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/367"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.69,0.02,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/367"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1017"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3879"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with colicky abdominal pain and vomiting for three days. He reports three months of weight loss and increasing abdominal bloating. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His mother and maternal aunt both developed endometrial cancer in their fifties, and his maternal grandfather died at age 42 years from what was described as \u0027liver cancer.\u0027 He has three healthy children and two younger brothers who are well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 125/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended with tenderness in the right upper quadrant. There are no abnormal skin findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA computed tomography scan reveals an obstructing tumour at the hepatic flexure. He undergoes an emergency right hemicolectomy. Histopathology shows a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma (T3 N0 M0) with no other polyps or abnormalities in the specimen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Familial adenomatous polyposis syndrome","Lynch syndrome","MUTYH-associated polyposis","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","Von Hippel-Lindau disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003ELynch syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer). The key features supporting this diagnosis are young age at presentation (39 years), right-sided colon cancer, absence of multiple polyps, and strong family history of Lynch syndrome-associated cancers (endometrial and possibly hepatobiliary). Lynch syndrome follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and accounts for about 3% of all colorectal cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial adenomatous polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the development of hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps throughout the colon, typically beginning in adolescence. The absence of multiple polyps in the surgical specimen makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMUTYH-associated polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal recessive condition characterised by multiple colorectal adenomas (usually 10-100) and an increased risk of colorectal cancer. The absence of multiple polyps and the strong family history make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by multiple hamartomatous polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract and distinctive mucocutaneous pigmentation. The absence of characteristic melanin spots on the lips and oral mucosa, and the absence of hamartomatous polyps make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Hippel-Lindau disease\u003C/strong\u003E primarily causes central nervous system and retinal hemangioblastomas, clear cell renal cell carcinomas, and pheochromocytomas. It rarely affects the gastrointestinal tract and is not associated with colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lynch syndrome (hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer) typically presents with right-sided colon cancer in younger patients without multiple polyps.","Family history of endometrial cancer and early-onset colorectal cancer are key features of Lynch syndrome.","Lynch syndrome follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and requires genetic counselling for family members."],"references":["Vasen HF. Clinical description of the Lynch syndrome [hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC)]. Fam Cancer. 2005;4(3):219-25. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16136381/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"367"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c